    "summary": "Vote B: Afterword, not Preface — would spoil Appendix's closing",
    "content": "B — the Translator's Afterword. This is precisely the kind of cross-traditional insight that belongs in Section B (existentialist positioning) after the reader has encountered the author's closing gesture in the Appendix. Placing it in the Preface would pre-interpret the Appendix's culminating passage before the reader experiences it — and that passage (\"我们正是这样的创造者，是自己生命和感受的诗人\") has its own experiential force as a closing statement that should arrive fresh. In the Afterword, the five-point comparison with Heidegger's Dichter enriches the reader's retrospective understanding of what they've already felt. The shift from \"How do I become authentic?\" to \"How do I notice that I already am?\" is a perfect capstone for the existentialist subsection and connects naturally to the \"livability\" theme already planned for that section."
